  "prompt": "How does blood flow from the heart to the brain?",
  "response": "Blood flows from the heart to the brain through the following path:\n\n1. Left Ventricle\n- Blood is pumped out of the heart's left ventricle through the aorta\n- This is oxygenated blood from the lungs\n\n2. Aortic Arch\n- The aorta curves and branches into major arteries\n- Two key arteries branch off: the left and right carotid arteries\n\n3. Carotid Arteries\n- These arteries run up both sides of the neck\n- They deliver blood directly to the brain\n- The internal carotid arteries supply most of the brain's blood\n\n4. Circle of Willis\n- A circular network of arteries at the base of the brain\n- Helps distribute blood evenly and provides backup routes if one artery is blocked\n\n5. Cerebral Arteries\n- Branch out from the Circle of Willis\n- Distribute blood to different regions of the brain\n- Include anterior, middle, and posterior cerebral arteries\n\n6. Capillaries\n- Smallest blood vessels that allow oxygen and nutrients to be exchanged with brain tissue\n\nThis complex pathway ensures the brain receives a constant, oxygen-rich blood supply essential for its functioning.",
